  "summary": "Dr. Ross and the narrator, Mr. Anstruther, visit Mary-Annichelle, a woman referred to as \"the Auntie,\" who lives in a state of confusion and believes her dreams are more real than her waking life. During the visit, Anstruther mentions a destroyed monastery and a wall marked with a \"Death Hound\" shape that has terrified local farmers. Upon hearing this, Mary-Annichelle becomes hysterical, claiming her memories are true and recounting how she used a specific power to unleash the \"death hound\" on people who ignored her warnings at an altar.\n\nAfter Dr. Ross administers a liquid to calm her, Mary-Annichelle describes a circular city composed of three rings for gods, priestesses, and priests, with a \"house of crystal\" at its center. As she mentions the crystal house, she traces circles on her forehead before suddenly regaining her composure and forgetting her words.\n\nOutside, Anstruther suggests that Mary-Annichelle is deranged, but Dr. Ross posits that what appears supernatural might actually be natural laws not yet understood, such as the ability to exert destructive force through willpower. Ross reveals he has been conducting experiments with crystals, noting that a previous patient reacted to a crystal by kneeling and claiming that \"faith still exists\" before passing out. Ross intends to conduct a further experiment the following day by having a patient gaze at a crystal, a topic that causes him to become uncharacteristically stiff and formal when questioned by Anstruther.",
